Appendix AR.4.3: Operational Classification and Phenomenological Bounds

The macro-transfer operator T_{\text{macro}}(k) defined in Eq. (AR.4.1) is classified as a phenomenological effective field theory (EFT) kernel, rather than a closed-form ab initio model of cosmic evolution. Its role is to provide a numerically stable ansatz for parameterizing scale-dependent torsional modulations within the linear Einstein–Boltzmann perturbation regime.

By construction, the kernel separates infrared (IR) and ultraviolet (UV) modifications in a controlled manner, avoiding discontinuities or instabilities in standard Boltzmann integration frameworks. The parameters \alpha and c_1 should therefore be interpreted as effective, scale-dependent coupling coefficients defining a restricted phenomenological parameter space rather than fundamental constants.

Within this interpretation, observational mappings derived from T_{\text{macro}}(k) represent structural sensitivity probes for cosmological tensions (e.g., H_0, S_8), rather than unique or complete resolutions. Any definitive claims require full nonlinear sampling against CMB likelihoods using a calibrated MCMC pipeline with high-redshift data constraints.

